from manim import *

# Define a custom Square class that inherits from Square
class MySquare(Square):
    # Decorate a method with @override_animation, specifying FadeIn
    @override_animation(FadeIn)
    def _fade_in_override(self, **kwargs):
        # This method will be called instead of the default FadeIn
        # Return the Create animation targeting 'self' (the MySquare instance)
        return Create(self, **kwargs)

# Example scene demonstrating the overridden animation
class OverrideAnimationExample(Scene):
    def construct(self):
        my_square = MySquare()
        # When self.play(FadeIn(...)) is called on MySquare,
        # the _fade_in_override method runs, executing Create(my_square)
        self.play(FadeIn(my_square))
```

Yes, you can control the alignment of content within table cells using the `arrange_in_grid_config` parameter during table initialization. Pass a dictionary containing configuration options for the underlying `arrange_in_grid` method. To align content to the right, use `"cell_alignment": RIGHT`.

